Section 1:
SCR 21 Text skip navigation SENATE PRESIDENT SENATORS COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS SENATE CLERK SENATE RULES HOUSE SPEAKER DELEGATES COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS HOUSE CLERK HOUSE RULES HOUSE STAFF JOINT INTERIM COMMITTEES LEGISLATIVE ADMINISTRATOR LEGISLATIVE SERVICES DIVISION PUBLIC INFORMATION LEGISLATIVE AUTOMATED SYSTEMS DIVISION LEGISLATIVE AUDITOR'S OFFICE PERFORMANCE EVALUATION & RESEARCH DIVISION POST AUDIT DIVISION BUDGET DIVISION REGULATORY AND FISCAL AFFAIRS DIVISION CLAIMS COMMISSION CRIME VICTIMS RULE-MAKING REVIEW SPECIAL INVESTIGATIONS JUDICIAL COMP. COMMISSION JOINT RULES STAFF INFO BILL STATUS BILL STATUS BILL TRACKING STATE LAW WEST VIRGINIA CODE ACTS OF THE LEGISLATURE CODE OF 1931 WV CONSTITUTION US CONSTITUTION REPORTS AGENCY REPORTS AGENCY GRANT AWARDS PERFORMANCE EVALUATIONS POST AUDITS EDUCATIONAL CITIZEN’S GUIDE INTERNSHIP PROGRAM PAGE PROGRAM PUBLICATIONS PHOTO GALLERY CAPITOL HISTORY HOW A BILL BECOMES LAW CONTACT SENATE ROSTER HOUSE ROSTER PUBLIC INFO. NEWS RELEASES HELPFUL LINKS Introduced Version Senate Concurrent Resolution 21 History |  Email Key: Green = existing Code. Red = new code to be enacted SENATE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION 21(By Senator Deeds)[Introduced March 24, 2025]Requesting a study of trends in the rates of reports, arrests, and convictions for sexual assault crimes in the State of West Virginia through the previous 10 years, including the rates or ratios of reports of sexual assault offenses to arrests, the rates of convictions to charges filed, the types or classification of offenses for which offenders are ultimately convicted, other types of dispositions for charges of sexual assault, and possible reasons for any trends observed in the data collected.Whereas, Statistics collected through the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) system reveal that West Virginia ranks 17th nationwide in reports of forcible rape submitted to law enforcement; and Whereas, The Bureau of Justice Statistics for the United States Department of Justice has published data indicating that the rates of sexual assaults have risen; and Whereas, The National Sexual Violence Resource Center has reported that, during the same period, there has been a nationwide, declining trend in the percentage of sexual assaults that are reported to police; andWhereas, Nationwide reports and analysis of trends in the reporting and prosecution of crimes of sexual violence are generally delayed for periods of years while the data is collected, analyzed, subjected to peer review, and then published, making it difficult to obtain valid information for the most recent years; andWhereas, Among all types of violent crime, sexual assault is least likely to result in an arrest and the Bureau of Justice Statistics has reported that 88 percent of sexual assault assaults in West Virginia are not cleared through arrest of a perpetrator; therefore, be it Resolved by the Legislature of West Virginia:The Joint Committee on Government and Finance is hereby requested to conduct a study of trends in the rates of reports, arrests, and convictions for sexual assault crimes in the State of West Virginia through the previous 10 years, including the rates or ratios of reports of sexual assault offenses to arrests, the rates of convictions to charges filed, the types or classification of offenses for which offenders are ultimately convicted, other types of dispositions for charges of sexual assault; and possible reasons for any trends observed in the data collected; and, be it Further Resolved, That the Joint Committee on Government and Finance report to the regular session of the Legislature, 2026, on its findings, conclusions, and recommendations, together with drafts of any legislation to effectuate its recommendations; and, be itFurther Resolved, That the expenses necessary to conduct this study, to prepare a report, and to draft necessary legislation be paid from legislative appropriations to the Joint Committee on Government and Finance. 